result.execSummary:
The defendant Caitlin M Strese was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Reserve Judge Sarah O'Brien presiding for Branch IV:

[MA]Cases 16CF216 & 15CM396 called together at 1:49pm 
Defendant Caitlin M Strese in court with Attorney Jordan Lippert.  Theresa A Beck appears for the State of Wisconsin.
  
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; pleas of "NO CONTEST  " entered on Counts #3 and #4 of Case 15CM396; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; the Court accepts plea, finds the Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads in and dismisses: Case 16CF216 Count #2

Sentencing arguments given by Counsel

On Count #3: The Court sentences Defendant to:
--serve 30  days in Jefferson County Jail, with Huber privileges; to commence on   7/25/2017 at 6:00pm
--3 days credit for time already served given
--pay costs of $243  plus $200 DNA surcharge

On Count #4: The Court sentences Defendant to:
--serve 30  days in Jefferson County Jail, with Huber privileges; to be served consecutive to the sentence in Count #3
--0 days credit for time already served given
--pay costs of $243  plus $200 DNA surcharge

Total costs plus $86 subpoena fees are  to be paid in $50 per month installments commencing on8/20/17 and on the 20th day of each month thereafter until paid in full; non-payment shall result in a 19  day jail term.
